<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06270103 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06270103 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  CONSUMER; TELEPHONE; REACTION; US; GOVERNMENT; BOAT; TAX  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  BOAT OWNERS agitated about new federal user fees can vent frustration bytelephone thanks to a service offered by a Palm Beach, Fla., business.;   BobHenslee, president of the Jupiter Telephone Co., says callers' recordedmessages will be forwarded to President Bush in an attempt at having theannual tax repealed.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Venture  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  BOAT OWNERS MAD AT FEES CAN VENT IRE OVER PHONE  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     The Boat Owners' Association of the United States, a lobbying group forrecreational boaters, is skeptical of the hotline, however.;   &quot;This could beused for good purposes, but at this point I have yet to find anything to leadme to believe it will be,&quot; said Michael Sciulla, a lobbyist for BOAT/U.S.;  User fees for recreational boaters have been proposed in Congress annually for11 years. Until this year, however, no such tax was ever passed.;   Fewboating-related measures have ever proved as unpopular.;   All recreationalmotorboats larger than 16 feet, using waters influenced by tides, weresupposed to be displaying a federal decal by Sept. 1. Decals, valid until Dec.31, cost $25 to $100, depending on vessel size. Those who do not comply risk a$5,000 fine.;   Money collected is to be used to defray the federal deficit.None will be returned to the Coast Guard and no new services will be renderedto boaters as a result.;   IF YOU'RE INTERESTED; Boat owners angry with newuser fees can vent their frustration by calling (900) 988-8443. The cost is$1.56 for the first minute and $1.23 for each additional minute.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Knight-Ridder News Service  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910926  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Thursday  </DAY><MONTH>  September  </MONTH><PG.COL>  8D  </PG.C